# claude-faa-nasr-skill — local configuration
#
# Copy this file to one of:
#   - ./config.sh           (next to this skill's SKILL.md)
#   - ${XDG_CONFIG_HOME:-$HOME/.config}/faa-nasr-skill/config.sh
#
# Or export the variables in your shell rc. Discovery order used by
# scripts/load-config.sh:
#
#   1. Existing environment variable
#   2. $FAA_NASR_CONFIG (if set, treated as a path to a config file)
#   3. ./config.sh next to the skill
#   4. $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/faa-nasr-skill/config.sh (or ~/.config/...)
#   5. The defaults baked into load-config.sh
#
# All variables below are optional — the defaults shown in comments
# are used if neither env nor file sets them.

# Where the built NASR databases (.sqlite + .parquet + CYCLE.txt) live.
# NASR_DATA_DIR="$HOME/data/faa/nasr"

# Where the processFaaData build tool is cloned.
# PROCESS_FAA_DATA_DIR="$HOME/src/processFaaData"

# Optional: directory of ADS-B parquet files for cross-format joins.
# Leave unset if you don't have an ADS-B archive — the relevant
# cookbook recipes will be skipped.
# ADSB_PARQUET_DIR="$HOME/data/adsb/parquet"

# sqlite3 binary that supports `.load mod_spatialite`. Apple's stock
# /usr/bin/sqlite3 does NOT — it's built with SQLITE_OMIT_LOAD_EXTENSION.
# scripts/doctor.sh auto-detects on macOS arm64, macOS x86, and Linux,
# but you can pin one here:
# SQLITE_BIN="/opt/homebrew/opt/sqlite/bin/sqlite3"   # macOS arm64
# SQLITE_BIN="/usr/local/opt/sqlite/bin/sqlite3"      # macOS x86
# SQLITE_BIN="sqlite3"                                # Linux (PATH)

# Full path to the mod_spatialite shared library. On macOS the
# loader's search path doesn't include Homebrew's lib dir for sqlite
# child processes, so a bare `mod_spatialite` won't resolve. Linux
# loaders find it by bare name. doctor.sh auto-detects; pin here if
# auto-detection fails:
# MOD_SPATIALITE_PATH="/opt/homebrew/lib/mod_spatialite.dylib"     # macOS arm64
# MOD_SPATIALITE_PATH="/usr/local/lib/mod_spatialite.dylib"        # macOS x86
# MOD_SPATIALITE_PATH="mod_spatialite"                             # Linux
